root.pub-comments: This tree was composed using a phylogenetic approach. Greenhill and Gray note that when a subgroup appear twice (or more) in the tree, it indicates that those subgroups are not monophyletic, i.e. not related to a single stock (2009:11). Also: “There is no unified Formosan subgroup but at least seven higher-order branches of Formosan derived from Proto Austronesian” (Greenhill and Gray 2009:11).
root.geography: spoken in Island Southeast Asia, New Guinea, and Oceania
root.publications: Gray, Russell D. & Simon J. Greenhill. 2009. Austronesian language phylogenies: myths and misconceptions about Bayesian computational methods. In K. Alexander Adelaar & Andrew K Pawley (eds.), Austronesian historical linguistics and culture history: a festschrift for Robert Blust, Pacific Linguistics, vol. 601, 1-23. Canberra: Pacific Linguistics.

child.pub-comments: “The first of these Oceanic subgroups is comprised of the Papuan Tip, North New Guinea and Meso-Melanesian languages. This represents the Western Oceanic group identified by Ross (1988). However, only the Willaumez languages of Meso-Melanesian are in this subgroup, the remainder is located in our second Oceanic grouping” (Greenhill and Gray 2009:12).
